USA: Alaska tightens pollution controls on timber firm.Alaska tightens pollution controls on timber firm.State officials said Alaska has tightened air pollution controls on Ketchikan Pulp Co., a major logging firm that has been under scrutiny in recent years for its air and water pollution practices.Officials said the firm was granted a new air-quality permit based on a recent decree that mandates reductions in sulphur dioxide emissions and controls of several other air pollutants.The new permit, issued by state environmental authorities, was filed on Friday.Ketchikan Pulp, owned by Louisiana-Pacific Corp., operates a dissolving-pulp mill in Ketchikan, Alaska, and sawmills in the area. It is the biggest timber operator in southeast Alaska's Tongass National Forest.